44:17.344 --> 44:19.829
[scary music]

44:22.245 --> 44:23.350
I was born in mine.

44:23.350 --> 44:28.217
[tense music]
[raindrops splattering]

44:29.667 --> 44:31.669
- If you were to look at the
sort of killer cross dresser

44:31.669 --> 44:34.292
or the murderous man
in a dress type trope,

44:34.292 --> 44:36.052
Hitchcock was not the
first one to do it.

44:36.052 --> 44:39.228
But "Psycho" is certainly like
the best known example of it.

44:40.885 --> 44:44.716
- There are a lot of movies
about men who dress up as women

44:44.716 --> 44:46.407
and use that as a
way to gain entry

44:46.407 --> 44:49.548
to spaces that women
are traditionally in.

44:49.548 --> 44:51.171
Famously, you have Norman Bates

44:51.171 --> 44:53.449
in Marion Crane's
bathroom in "Psycho,"

44:53.449 --> 44:57.073
which is kind of the original
trans bathroom panic.

44:57.073 --> 44:59.144
[shower rod squeaking]
[scary music]

44:59.144 --> 45:01.215
[Marion screaming]
- Hitchcock captured

45:01.215 --> 45:04.702
the essence of female as victim.

45:04.702 --> 45:07.635
[creepy music]
[Marion screaming]

45:07.635 --> 45:11.709
He was able to raise that
ideal to such a height.

45:12.710 --> 45:15.126
[creepy music]

45:15.126 --> 45:17.093
I mean half the country
stopped showering.

45:17.093 --> 45:18.681
[show curtain rings clicking]

45:18.681 --> 45:19.924
[body thudding]

45:19.924 --> 45:21.719
- One of the scariest
things about "Psycho,"

45:21.719 --> 45:23.617
before we get to
the shower scene,

45:23.617 --> 45:26.689
is Marion Crane's
moral ambiguity.

45:26.689 --> 45:29.450
This is something that
is so truly upsetting

45:29.450 --> 45:31.383
at the time in 1960,

45:31.383 --> 45:35.905
that he very overtly
begins the film with her

45:35.905 --> 45:37.976
in her black brassiere.

45:37.976 --> 45:41.462
He is laying bare the
fact that this is a woman

45:41.462 --> 45:44.880
who is essentially, quote,
